<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-245-547  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 245 547.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic News  Jan 9 1989 v35 n1740 p28(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>AF picks up Raytheon for Jstars CPUs: militarized VAX line. (AirForce contract for Joint Surveillance Tactical Attack RadarSystem)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Robertson, Jack.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The US Air Force assigns the Joint Surveillance Tactical AttackRadar System (Jstars) computer system contract to Raytheon.andP;  Thefirm will supply militarized VAX minicomputers which will replacethe Loral Rolm military specification (Mil-Spec) Hawk computercurrently in use.andP;  The Air Force Electronic Systems Div alsointends to replace the Rolm militarized disk drives used on Jstarsbut will take open bids for that contract.andP;  Raytheon stands toprofit from a planned upgrade of the Jstars ground terminals tomilitarized VAX terminals if its only competitor, Norden Systems,does not receive the contract.andP;  Raytheon has militarized a laterversion of the VAX than Norden, and Norden is not expected tocompete for the contract.andP;  The Air Force Space Div also intends topurchase militarized VAXes for its airborne control planes for theMilstar communication satellite network.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Raytheon Co. (contracts).andO;Ticker:    RTN.andO;Topic:     United States. Air ForceMilitaryMinicomputersDefense ContractsIndustry AnalysisJSTARS (Electronic equipment).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>